  "biography_html": "<div class=\"research-section\">\n<p class=\"research-text\">Lesbonax of Mytilene was a Greek rhetorician and orator of the 1st century BCE. A native of Mytilene on Lesbos, he was the son of Sthenelaus and a contemporary of Cicero. According to the Suda, he taught rhetoric in his hometown and counted Potamo, the future founder of an eclectic philosophical school in Alexandria, among his pupils.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">His literary output consisted of orations. The Suda credits him with three political speeches, though their titles are not recorded. No complete works survive; his writings are considered lost and are known only through later references.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">Lesbonax is a minor figure in Hellenistic rhetoric, primarily significant for his role as a teacher and his link to the more prominent Potamo of Alexandria. His lost corpus prevents a detailed assessment of his oratorical style, but his career exemplifies the continuity of Greek rhetorical education in the Eastern Mediterranean during the late Hellenistic period.</p>\n</div>",
